# Container Scroll-State Queries - Technical Details

## 1. Syntax for Declaring a Scroll-State Container

To establish a container as a scroll-state query container, use the `container-type` property with the value `scroll-state`:

```css
.container {
  container-type: scroll-state;
  container-name: my-container;  /* optional */
}
```

**Properties:**
- `container-type: scroll-state` - Required to enable scroll-state queries on this element
- `container-name: <identifier>` - Optional, allows targeting specific containers in queries

## 2. Scroll-State Query Syntax

General syntax for all scroll-state queries:

```css
@container [container-name] scroll-state(descriptor: value) {
  /* CSS rules */
}
```

The scroll-state descriptors are enclosed in parentheses: `scroll-state(...)`

## 3. Query Types and Values

### `scrollable` Query
Tests whether a container can be scrolled in a given direction via user-initiated scrolling.

```css
@container my-container scroll-state(scrollable: top) {
  /* Applied if container can scroll toward top edge */
}
```

**Keyword values:**
- `top` - Can scroll toward top edge
- `inline-end` - Can scroll toward inline-end edge
- `y` - Can scroll in either or both y-axis directions

### `scrolled` Query
Tests whether a container was most recently scrolled in a given direction.

```css
@container scroller scroll-state(scrolled: block-start) {
  /* Applied if recently scrolled toward block-start */
}

@container scroller scroll-state(scrolled: block-end) {
  /* Applied if recently scrolled toward block-end */
}
```

**Keyword values:**
- `block-start` - Scrolled toward block-start edge
- `right` - Scrolled toward right edge
- `y` - Scrolled up or down along y-axis
- `none` - Not a scroll container or hasn't been scrolled

### `snapped` Query
Tests whether a container is snapped to a scroll-snap container ancestor along a given axis.

```css
@container snap-container scroll-state(snapped: y) {
  .wrapper {
    background: purple;
    color: white;
  }
}
```

**Keyword values:**
- `x` - Snapping horizontally
- `inline` - Snapping in inline direction
- `y` - Snapping vertically or in both directions
- `none` - Not snapped to any scroll-snap container

**Requirements:**
- Container must have a scroll-snap container ancestor with `scroll-snap-type` value other than `none`
- Evaluation occurs when the `scrollsnapchanging` event fires on the scroll snap container

### `stuck` Query
Tests whether a `position: sticky` container is stuck to an edge of its scroll container ancestor.

```css
@container sticky-heading scroll-state(stuck: top) {
  h2, p {
    background: #cccccc;
    box-shadow: 0 5px 2px #00000077;
  }
}
```

**Keyword values:**
- `top` - Stuck to top edge
- `block-end` - Stuck to block-end edge
- `none` - Not stuck to any edge

## 4. Complete Code Example: Snapped State Detection

### HTML Structure
```html
<main>
  <section>
    <div class="wrapper">
      <h2>Section 1</h2>
    </div>
  </section>
  <!-- More sections... -->
</main>
```

### CSS Implementation

```css
/* Scroll container with snap functionality */
main {
  overflow: scroll;
  scroll-snap-type: y mandatory;
  height: 450px;
  width: 250px;
  border: 3px solid black;
}

/* Snap targets */
section {
  font-family: "Helvetica", "Arial", sans-serif;
  width: 150px;
  height: 150px;
  margin: 50px auto;
  scroll-snap-align: center;

  /* Enable as scroll-state query container */
  container-type: scroll-state;
  container-name: snap-container;
}

/* Default wrapper styling */
.wrapper {
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  border-radius: 5px;
  background: #eeeeee;
  box-shadow:
    inset 1px 1px 4px rgb(255 255 255 / 0.5),
    inset -1px -1px 4px rgb(0 0 0 / 0.5);

  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;

  transition:
    0.6s background,
    0.6s color;
}

/* Apply styles when section is snapped */
@container snap-container scroll-state(snapped: y) {
  .wrapper {
    background: purple;
    color: white;
  }
}
```

## 5. Browser Support Note

The page includes a fallback for browsers that don't support `scroll-state` container queries:

```css
@supports not (container-type: scroll-state) {
  body::before {
    content: "Your browser does not support `scroll-state` container queries.";
    color: black;
    background-color: wheat;
    position: fixed;
    left: 0;
    right: 0;
    top: 40%;
    text-align: center;
    padding: 1rem 0;
    z-index: 1;
  }
}
```

## Key Points

1. **Container declaration** requires `container-type: scroll-state` on the element to be queried
2. **Snapped queries** specifically detect scroll-snap alignment states
3. **Query syntax** uses `scroll-state(descriptor: value)` format
4. **Multiple queries** can target the same container with different descriptors
5. **Smooth transitions** can be applied to properties that change when query states match/unmatch

